{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 Calibri;}{\f1 Courier New;}}\paperw11907\paperh16840\margl1440\margr1440\margt1080\margb1080\fs22 Unit Converter Console\line \line Assignment Information\line Dar es Salaam Institute of Technology\line Civil Engineering Department\line Module: Programming Fundamentals for Technicians (GST 05117)\line Class: OD24CE-2 | Assignment Type: Group | Assignment No: 3\line Group Number: 11 | Submission Date: March 1, 2026\line \line Group Members\line 1. ABDULAZIZ MAHYORO (240121429579)\line 2. LAWRENCE MMATAMBWE (220121417491)\line 3. ELIAH HANGO (240121476067)\line 4. HUSSEIN OMARY (240121449049)\line 5. ROBERT JAMES (240121479897)\line 6. GIDEON OLANG'U (240121429421)\line 7. MOSES MFUSE (24012317533)\line 8. GLORIA DAUDI (240121453512)\line \line Brief Explanation (One-Page Summary)\line In this mini project, our group focused on a clear problem that can be solved using basic C concepts learned in class. The objective of this work is to take user input, apply program logic step by step, and produce understandable results.\line In this project (Unit Converter Console), converter app for temperature, length, and weight units in a menu-driven interface.\line \line How the Program Works\line 1. It shows a clear prompt/menu to the user.\line 2. It accepts and validates user input to avoid wrong values.\line 3. It processes data using conditions, loops, and calculations.\line 4. It prints final results in a readable format.\line \line Concepts Practiced\line - Functions\line - Conditionals\line - Switch statements\line - Arithmetic formulas\line - Input validation\line \line Sample Output (short example)\line === Unit Converter Console ===\line 1. Temperature Converter\line 2. Length Converter\line 3. Weight Converter\line 4. Exit\line Choose an option: 1\line Temperature Converter\line 1. Celsius to Fahrenheit\line \line Presentation Note\line This mini project is intentionally simple, focused, and easy to explain during presentation.}